Prostomium fusiform, rounded anteriorly (
Fig. 3A–D
), with a long and slender subdistal pad surrounding the ventral region (
Fig. 3A–D
); posteriorly blunt, extending to anterior margin of chaetiger 1 (
Fig. 3A–B
). Two pairs of black subdermal eyes, arranged in a trapezoid; anterior pair small, crescent-shaped, posterior pair large, rounded (
Fig. 3A–B
). Palps located lateral to prostomium (some 
paratypes
with palps lost). Palps long, extending up to chaetiger 5, densely ciliated on frontal surfaces (
Fig. 3E
). Peristomium large, expanded laterally, partially surrounding the prostomium, and extending around base of palps, forming short lateral wings, fused dorsally from chaetiger 1 (
Fig. 3A–B, E–F
).

Branchiae present on chaetiger 1, inserted just posterior to prostomium; surfaces wrinkled, thick (
Fig. 3E
), heavily ciliated; branchiae long, extending up to chaetiger 6, about the same length, but slightly thicker than palps. Conical papilla absent between branchiae (
Fig. 3A–B
).

Parapodia on chaetiger 1 with neuropodial postchaetal lamellae only; notopodial lamellae lacking, but with 1– 4 long capillaries present on the notopodium (
Fig. 3A–B
); neuropodial postchaetal lamellae on chaetiger 1 large, oval (
Fig. 3A–B, F
), slightly inclined. Notopodial postchaetal lamellae on chaetiger 2 dorsally rounded and triangular on ventral edges (
Fig. 3G
); united across dorsum, forming a high dorsal membranous collar (
Fig. 3A–B, G
); notopodium on chaetiger 3 oval large (
Fig. 3H
); notopodia largest on chaetigers 2–3, becoming low, wider and more rounded on chaetigers 4–8 (

Fig. 
3I

). Notopodial lamellae disappearing from chaetigers 11–13 until the end (
Fig. 3J
). Anterior notopodial prechaetal lamellae low, middle and posterior chaetigers absent.

Neuropodial postchaetal lamellae rounded throughout (
Fig. 3H, F
), except the neuropodium on chaetiger 2 which is slightly angled and trapezium-shaped, ventrally directed (
Fig. 3G
); larger than other neuropodial lamellae. Neuropodial lamellae disappearing from chaetigers 8–10 until the end (
Fig. 3J, P
). Neuropodial prechaetal lamellae on chaetiger 1 low, rudimentary on succeeding chaetigers. Interparapodial pouches lacking.

All notopodial and neuropodial capillaries arranged in one row. Notopodial and neuropodial capillaries on anterior chaetigers slightly granulated, alimbate (
Fig. 3K, L
); notopodial capillaries on middle and posterior chaetigers slender, smooth and alimbate. Sabre chaetae on neuropodia from chaetiger 3 (stouter on chaetiger 7), up to two per fascicle; each chaeta stout, curved, slightly granulated, alimbate (
Fig. 3M
). Neuropodial hooded hooks (
Fig. 3N
) from chaetigers 7–9 (
holotype
9), up to nine per fascicle, accompanied by short, slender, alimbate capillaries (
Fig. 3O
); all hooks with 4–5 pairs of small teeth above main tooth, without secondary hoods; main hood very large (
Fig. 3
N’). Notopodial hooded hooks absent.

Some of the specimens examined were females with oval-shaped oocytes in brood structures in the coelomic cavities (
Fig. 3Q
) between segments 21–31, measuring 38/50–66/90 µm in diameter. Females carried eggs in spring.

Methyl green staining pattern:
from posterior margin of chaetiger 3 up to chaetiger 8 tissues stained profusely with methyl green (
Fig. 3C
).
